<p class=3D"note">note: images taken with a 200 mm lens (320 mm field of vi=
ew on a 35 mm camera)</p>
<h2>CLARIFICATION: FOCAL LENGTH AND DEPTH OF FIELD</h2>
<p>Note that focal length has not been listed as influencing depth of field=
, contrary to popular belief. Even though <a href=3D"https://www.cambridgei=
ncolour.com/tutorials/telephoto-lenses.htm">telephoto lenses</a> appear to =
create a much shallower depth of field, this is mainly because they are oft=
en used to magnify the subject when one is unable to get closer. If the sub=
ject occupies the same fraction of the image (constant magnification) for b=
oth a telephoto and a <a href=3D"https://www.cambridgeincolour.com/tutorial=
s/wide-angle-lenses.htm">wide angle lens</a>, the <em>total depth of field =
is virtually* constant with focal length</em>! This would of course require=
 you to either get much closer with a wide angle lens or much farther with =
a telephoto lens, as demonstrated in the following chart:</p>
